#. Tag: title
#: vt_installation.xml:237
#, no-c-format
msgid "Installing UEFI support"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:240
#, no-c-format
msgid "&kvm; guests support &uefisecboot; by using the OVMF firmware. &xen; HVM guests support booting from the OVMF firmware as well, but they do not support &uefisecboot;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:247
#, no-c-format
msgid "UEFI support is provided by <emphasis>OVMF</emphasis> ( <emphasis>Open Virtual Machine Firmware</emphasis> ). To enable UEFI boot, first install the <package>qemu-ovmf-x86_64</package> or <package>qemu-uefi-aarch64</package> package depending on the architecture of the guest."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:254
#, no-c-format
msgid "The firmware used by virtual machines is auto-selected. The auto-selection is based on the JSON files in the firmware package described above. The &libvirt; &qemu; driver parses those files when loading so it knows the capabilities of the various types of firmware. Then when the user selects the type of firmware and any desired features (for example, support for &uefisecboot;), &libvirt; will be able to find a firmware file that satisfies the user's requirements."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:264
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example, to specify EFI with &uefisecboot;, use the following configuration:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_installation.xml:269
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&lt;os firmware='efi'&gt;\n"
      " &lt;loader secure='yes'/&gt;\n"
      "&lt;/os&gt;\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:275
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <package>qemu-ovmf-x86_64</package> package contains the following important UEFI firmware images. They provide &uefisecboot; capability for various &vmguest;s:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_installation.xml:281
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&prompt.root;<command>rpm -ql qemu-ovmf-x86_64</command>\n"
      "[...]\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/ovmf-x86_64-smm-ms-code.bin\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/ovmf-x86_64-smm-ms-vars.bin\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/ovmf-x86_64-smm-opensuse-code.bin\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/ovmf-x86_64-smm-opensuse-vars.bin\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/ovmf-x86_64-smm-suse-code.bin\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/ovmf-x86_64-smm-suse-vars.bin\n"
      "[...]\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:295
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use &uefisecboot; for &sle; guests, use the <filename>ovmf-x86_64-smm-suse-code.bin</filename> firmware."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:301
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use &uefisecboot; for &opensuse; guests, use the <filename>ovmf-x86_64-smm-opensuse-code.bin</filename> firmware."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:307
#, no-c-format
msgid "To use &uefisecboot; for &mswin; guests, use the <filename>ovmf-x86_64-smm-ms-code.bin</filename> firmware."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:314
#, no-c-format
msgid "For the &aarch64; architecture, the package is named <package>qemu-uefi-aarch32</package> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_installation.xml:319
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&prompt.root;<command>rpm -ql qemu-uefi-aarch32</command>\n"
      "[...]\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/aavmf-aarch32-code.bin\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/aavmf-aarch32-vars.bin\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/firmware\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/firmware/60-aavmf-aarch32.json\n"
      "/usr/share/qemu/qemu-uefi-aarch32.bin\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:329
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <filename>*-code.bin</filename> files are the UEFI firmware files. The <filename>*-vars.bin</filename> files are corresponding variable store images that can be used as a template for a per-VM non-volatile store. &libvirt; copies the specified <literal>vars</literal> template to a per-VM path under <filename>/var/lib/libvirt/qemu/nvram/</filename> when first creating the VM. Files without <literal>code</literal> or <literal>vars</literal> in the name can be used as a single UEFI image. They are not as useful since no UEFI variables persist across power cycles of the VM."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:341
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <filename>*-ms*.bin</filename> files contain UEFI CA keys as found on real hardware. Therefore, they are configured as the default in &libvirt;. Likewise, the <filename>*-suse*.bin</filename> files contain preinstalled &suse; keys. There is also a set of files with no preinstalled keys."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:348
#, no-c-format
msgid "For details, see <xref linkend=\"vle-libvirt-inst-virt-install-ovmf\"/> and <link xlink:href=\"http://www.linux-kvm.org/downloads/lersek/ovmf-whitepaper-c770f8c.txt\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_installation.xml:358
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enable nested virtualization in &kvm;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_installation.xml:361
#, no-c-format
msgid "Technology preview"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:362
#, no-c-format
msgid "&kvm;'s nested virtualization is still a technology preview. It is provided for testing purposes and is not supported."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:368
#, no-c-format
msgid "Nested guests are &kvm; guests run in a &kvm; guest. When describing nested guests, we will use the following virtualization layers:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_installation.xml:375
#, no-c-format
msgid "L0"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:377
#, no-c-format
msgid "A bare metal host running &kvm;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_installation.xml:383
#, no-c-format
msgid "L1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:385
#, no-c-format
msgid "A virtual machine running on L0. Because it can run another &kvm;, it is called a <emphasis>guest hypervisor</emphasis> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: vt_installation.xml:392
#, no-c-format
msgid "L2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:394
#, no-c-format
msgid "A virtual machine running on L1. It is called a <emphasis>nested guest</emphasis> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:402
#, no-c-format
msgid "Nested virtualization has many advantages. You can benefit from it in the following scenarios:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:409
#, no-c-format
msgid "Manage your own virtual machines directly with your hypervisor of choice in cloud environments."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:415
#, no-c-format
msgid "Enable the live migration of hypervisors and their guest virtual machines as a single entity."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:420
#, no-c-format
msgid "Live migration of a nested &vmguest; is not supported."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:426
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use it for software development and testing."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:432
#, no-c-format
msgid "To enable nesting temporarily, remove the module and reload it with the <option>nested</option> &kvm; module parameter:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:439
#, no-c-format
msgid "For Intel CPUs, run:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_installation.xml:442
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&prompt.sudo;modprobe -r kvm_intel &amp;&amp; modprobe kvm_intel nested=1\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:447
#, no-c-format
msgid "For AMD CPUs, run:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_installation.xml:450
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&prompt.sudo;modprobe -r kvm_amd &amp;&amp; modprobe kvm_amd nested=1\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:456
#, no-c-format
msgid "To enable nesting permanently, enable the <option>nested</option> &kvm; module parameter in the <filename>/etc/modprobe.d/kvm_*.conf</filename> file, depending on your CPU:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:464
#, no-c-format
msgid "For Intel CPUs, edit <filename>/etc/modprobe.d/kvm_intel.conf</filename> and add the following line:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_installation.xml:468
#, no-c-format
msgid "options kvm_intel nested=1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:471
#, no-c-format
msgid "For AMD CPUs, edit <filename>/etc/modprobe.d/kvm_amd.conf</filename> and add the following line:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_installation.xml:475
#, no-c-format
msgid "options kvm_amd nested=1"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:479
#, no-c-format
msgid "When your L0 host is capable of nesting, you will be able to start an L1 guest in one of the following ways:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:486
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use the <option>-cpu host</option> &qemu; command line option."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:491
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add the <literal>vmx</literal> (for Intel CPUs) or the <literal>svm</literal> (for AMD CPUs) CPU feature to the <option>-cpu</option> &qemu; command line option, which enables virtualization for the virtual CPU."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: vt_installation.xml:501
#, no-c-format
msgid "&esx; as a guest hypervisor"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:502
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you use &esx; as a guest hypervisor on top of &kvm; bare metal hypervisor, you may experience unstable network communication. This problem happens especially between nested &kvm; guests and the &kvm; bare metal hypervisor or external network. The following default CPU configuration of the nested &kvm; guest is causing the problem:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_installation.xml:509
#, no-c-format
msgid "&lt;cpu mode='host-model' check='partial'/&gt;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: vt_installation.xml:510
#, no-c-format
msgid "To fix it, modify the CPU configuration as follow:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: vt_installation.xml:513
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "[...]\n"
      "&lt;cpu mode='host-passthrough' check='none'&gt;\n"
      " &lt;cache mode='passthrough'/&gt;\n"
      "&lt;/cpu&gt;\n"
      "[...]\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

